TS-AI-OS: A Truth-Seeking Cognitive AI Operating System

Toward Asymptotic Truth Convergence in Artificial Epistemic Agents

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

Contemporary artificial intelligence systems are optimized for performance metrics—accuracy, fluency, or reward—without explicit epistemic guarantees. They confidently produce falsehoods, ignore contradictions, and lack self‑correction mechanisms. Scientific inquiry, in contrast, treats truth as an asymptotic ideal approached through structured doubt, hypothesis testing, and contradiction resolution.

This thesis presents TS-AI-OS, a cognitive architecture whose sole objective is truth convergence. Knowledge is formalized as a probability distribution on a statistical manifold equipped with the Fisher information metric, and a contradiction potential penalizes logical inconsistencies. The system evolves via a natural gradient flow that minimizes a Lyapunov functional combining Kullback‑Leibler divergence to the truth and internal contradiction energy.

Three central theorems are proved. Global asymptotic stability shows that from any non‑dogmatic prior, the belief state converges to the unique truth point. An epistemic friction lemma demonstrates that adversarial noise below a critical information threshold is filtered out, guaranteeing robustness against hallucinations. Finite‑time contradiction resolution establishes that contradictions are resolved exponentially fast, with time logarithmic in the desired precision. A sparse contradiction tensor using geometric embedding and locality‑sensitive hashing achieves near‑linear computational scaling. An Epistemic Safety Layer provides Merkle‑based immutable audit trails, a falsifiability operator that prevents dogmatic beliefs, and source entropy caps to counter information laundering. A modular seven‑engine architecture implements the gradient flow with these safety guarantees.

The work offers the first system‑level blueprint for an artificial epistemic agent with rigorous geometric convergence guarantees, robustness to noise, scalable computation, and cryptographic auditability.

