Appendix B: Sparse Contradiction Tensor and Complexity Analysis

B.1 Geometric Embedding and Locality‑Sensitive Hashing

Let  \mathcal{E} : \Phi \to \mathbb{R}^d  be an embedding function such that for two propositions  \phi, \psi , the probability that they are contradictory decays exponentially with the Euclidean distance  \|\mathcal{E}(\phi) - \mathcal{E}(\psi)\| . Formally, there exist constants  \alpha, \beta > 0  such that

P(\mathcal{C}(\phi,\psi) = 1) \le \alpha e^{-\beta \|\mathcal{E}(\phi) - \mathcal{E}(\psi)\|}.

This assumption is satisfied by semantic encoders trained on contradiction datasets.

Locality‑sensitive hashing partitions  \mathbb{R}^d  into buckets. For a hash function family  \mathcal{H} , two points that are close are likely to collide. We use a standard LSH scheme with  L  hash tables, each with  K  concatenated hash functions. The expected number of false positive candidates per query is  O(\log n) .

B.2 Active Frontier Sampling

Let the active frontier  V_{\text{active}} \subset V  be the set of propositions with the highest “epistemic heat,” defined as

\text{heat}(\phi) = H(\pi(\phi)) + \sum_{\psi} \gamma(\phi,\psi) + \text{recency\_decay}(t_{\text{last}}).

The size of  V_{\text{active}}  is bounded by a constant  M  (e.g., 1000). All contradiction updates are performed only on pairs involving at least one node in  V_{\text{active}} . For nodes outside the active frontier, contradictions are assumed to be negligible or are checked only periodically.

B.3 Complexity Bound

Theorem B.1 (Sparse Efficiency). Under the exponential decay of contradiction probability with distance, and with LSH and active frontier, the expected time per update is  O(n \log n) , and the error in the truth metric due to sparsity is bounded by  \epsilon  when the conflict radius is chosen as  R \propto \log(1/\epsilon) .

Proof.
Each new proposition is inserted into the LSH indices. Querying for potential contradictory propositions costs  O(L \cdot \text{(bucket size)}) . With appropriate parameters, bucket size is  O(\log n)  in expectation, giving  O(\log n)  per query. Over  n  insertions, the total cost is  O(n \log n) .

The probability of missing a contradiction that would have been detected in the full  O(n^2)  check is bounded by the probability that the distance between contradictory propositions exceeds  R . By the exponential decay assumption, this probability is at most  \alpha e^{-\beta R} . Setting  R = \frac{1}{\beta} \log(\alpha/\epsilon)  ensures the miss probability is less than  \epsilon . The contribution of each missed contradiction to the truth metric error is at most its weight, which is bounded by  \gamma . Hence the total error is bounded by  \epsilon . ∎

