Appendix C: Merkle Tree Audit Trail Implementation

C.1 Data Structure

A Merkle tree is built incrementally. Each update  u_i  (hypothesis, evidence, contradiction, belief change) is hashed to a leaf:

h_i = \text{SHA256}(\text{type} \| \text{timestamp} \| \text{content\_hash} \| \text{source\_hash} \| \text{prev\_root}).

The tree is stored as a list of hashes; internal nodes are computed as needed for proofs. The root hash  R_t  is stored after each update.

C.2 Verification

To verify that a belief  b  is supported by a specific chain of evidence, the auditor requests a Merkle proof: the path from the leaf corresponding to the evidence to the root, along with sibling hashes. The auditor recomputes the root and compares it to the published root. If they match, the evidence was included in the audit trail at that time.

C.3 Security

The Merkle tree provides collision resistance (under SHA‑256). Any tampering with the audit trail would change the root hash, which is published immutably (e.g., on a blockchain or in a trusted log). This ensures that the system cannot retroactively alter its reasoning without detection.

